  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've noticed in my own life and the lives of many people around me. Growing up, I was taught that math and science were for boys, and as a woman, I often felt that I wasn't 'cut out' for these fields. Even though I never pursued a STEM degree myself, I've seen how this belief can hold people back. For instance, when I deliver packages in Los Angeles, I sometimes encounter people who assume I don't understand technology or engineering because they see me driving a delivery van. This kind of assumption isn't just about stereotypes—it's about how those stereotypes affect performance and confidence. I believe we should address stereotype threat in STEM because it has real consequences. If we don't tackle it, more talented individuals might not reach their full potential, especially women and people of color who are already underrepresented in these fields. The solution isn't about changing the curriculum or creating special programs for everyone—it's about changing the culture. Schools and workplaces need to foster environments where everyone feels valued and safe to explore their interests. I've found that simply talking about stereotypes and their effects can make a difference. In my community, we've started small by encouraging women to take STEM classes together, and it's made a big impact. It's not about fixing people—it's about fixing the systems that make them feel like they don't belong. I think that's something we all can work on, starting with ourselves.",
